<L=3J#m>Microformats rel property examples</L><I=m>
There are some microformats that are applied to a page by using a special  rel=  property. These
microformats describe a relation between a current document and a linked document. For a full list of
these, see the rel property on the microformats wiki.

<L=3J#n>rel=author</L><I=n>
This attribute states that the linked document represents the author of the current page.

html

```html
<a rel="author" href="https://jamesg.blog">James Gallagher</a>
```

<L=3J#o>rel=license</L><I=o>
This attribute states that the linked document contains the license under which the current page is
published.

html

```html
<a rel="license" href="https://mit-license.org/">MIT License</a>
```

<L=3J#p>rel=nofollow</L><I=p>
This attribute states that the linked document should not be given any weight by search engine ranking
algorithms that may derive from the current page. This is useful to prevent link graph algorithms from
weighing a page higher than it otherwise would after seeing a link to a document.

html

```html
<a rel="nofollow" href="https://jamesg.blog">James Gallagher</a>
```

<L=3J#q>Browser compatibility</L><I=q>
Supported in all browsers' support for the class attribute and its DOM API.

